1
00:00:06,000 --> 00:00:12,074
Delicious Vegan Sausages, Cheese
and Burgers - Vegusto.co.uk

2
00:00:29,029 --> 00:00:31,020
[ Pigs squealing ]

3
00:01:28,855 --> 00:01:31,050
MAN: As President Reagan
was preparing to deliver

4
00:01:31,124 --> 00:01:33,058
his weekly radio address
from Camp David,

5
00:01:33,126 --> 00:01:34,889
he ad-libbed
thoughts on the economy

6
00:01:34,961 --> 00:01:36,223
during a microphone check,

7
00:01:36,296 --> 00:01:38,457
not intended to be
part of his speech.

8
00:01:38,531 --> 00:01:40,089
PRESIDENT REAGAN:
My fellow Americans,

9
00:01:40,166 --> 00:01:43,067
I've talked to you
about the economic problems

10
00:01:43,136 --> 00:01:45,798
and opportunities
our nation faces.

11
00:01:45,872 --> 00:01:47,863
I'm prepared to tell you
it's a hell of mess.

12
00:01:47,941 --> 00:01:50,535
The hard line being taken
by the Reagan administration

13
00:01:50,610 --> 00:01:52,077
concerning
the air controllers strike...

14
00:01:52,145 --> 00:01:54,943
The Supreme Court delivered
a potentially staggering setback

15
00:01:55,014 --> 00:01:55,742
to labor unions.

16
00:01:55,815 --> 00:01:57,976
It comes at a time
when union officials

17
00:01:58,051 --> 00:02:01,680
are charging there is a growing
campaign to break unions.

18
00:02:01,754 --> 00:02:03,688
MAN:
The operation will be nonunion.

19
00:02:03,756 --> 00:02:05,724
Salaries will be cut in half.

20
00:02:05,792 --> 00:02:07,851
MAN #2: Wilson Foods
declared bankruptcy.

21
00:02:07,927 --> 00:02:10,691
With the stroke of a pen,
it could stay in business

22
00:02:10,763 --> 00:02:12,788
but void its labor contract

23
00:02:12,866 --> 00:02:15,699
and slash workers' salaries
by 40% to 50%.

24
00:02:15,768 --> 00:02:17,702
WOMAN: These are hard times
for the meatpacking industry.

25
00:02:17,770 --> 00:02:21,035
MAN: Union labor has taken
almost 50% wage-and-benefit cuts

26
00:02:21,107 --> 00:02:24,668
to keep their jobs
and their companies afloat.

27
00:02:24,744 --> 00:02:28,578
At least I'm taking some money
home instead of nothing.

28
00:02:28,648 --> 00:02:31,014
WOMAN: In Waterloo, Iowa,
a shutdown.

29
00:02:31,084 --> 00:02:32,642
At Iowa Beef,
a violent strike...

30
00:02:32,719 --> 00:02:35,119
MAN: Striking meatpackers
facing 40% pay cuts

31
00:02:35,188 --> 00:02:37,588
go packing bricks against
a truck at a Wilson Foods plant.

32
00:02:37,657 --> 00:02:40,990
RATHER: Crossed picket lines in
spite of an automobile barricade

33
00:02:41,060 --> 00:02:43,961
as Hormel's flagship plant,
open for a second week...

34
00:02:44,030 --> 00:02:47,056
WOMAN: ...send in the guards
was reached after city officials

35
00:02:47,133 --> 00:02:50,398
said the situation at Hormel
was beyond their control.

36
00:02:50,470 --> 00:02:52,370
This is not Austin anymore!

37
00:02:52,438 --> 00:02:53,837
It's Hormel, Minnesota!

38
00:02:53,907 --> 00:02:56,068
You guys are helping them!

39
00:03:03,750 --> 00:03:06,241
[ Cheers and applause ]

40
00:03:09,822 --> 00:03:14,759
Austin, Minnesota, is not
just about Austin, Minnesota.

41
00:03:14,827 --> 00:03:19,161
Austin is the cavalry.
The workers in this nation.

42
00:03:19,232 --> 00:03:25,364
Workers somewhere,
sometime, someplace,

43
00:03:25,438 --> 00:03:31,001
must stand up and say,
"Enough is enough!"

44
00:03:31,077 --> 00:03:34,171
We want jobs and justice.

45
00:03:40,286 --> 00:03:42,151
Someday.

46
00:03:59,838 --> 00:04:02,705
Can I give you a pamphlet here?

47
00:04:02,775 --> 00:04:06,836
So you can see what's going on
in the Austin plant. Thank you.

48
00:04:09,948 --> 00:04:13,975
Can I give you one of these
about the Hormel injury rate?

49
00:04:14,053 --> 00:04:15,850
- Okay, thank you.
- Thank you.

50
00:04:22,861 --> 00:04:24,385
Aren't you Mr. Anderson?

51
00:04:24,463 --> 00:04:26,954
Hi. I don't know
if you remember me.

52
00:04:27,032 --> 00:04:30,365
- We had the good years.
- You did.

53
00:04:30,436 --> 00:04:34,133
And this, I sure hope it comes,
gets straightened out.

54
00:04:34,206 --> 00:04:36,231
I'd like to see
something settled.

55
00:04:36,308 --> 00:04:39,368
And I understand
your side of it.

56
00:04:39,445 --> 00:04:42,744
I really do. I wouldn't
like to take a cut either.

57
00:04:42,815 --> 00:04:45,943
I wish everybody good luck.

58
00:04:46,018 --> 00:04:48,953
I hope they don't have trouble
with the company.

59
00:04:49,021 --> 00:04:53,685
I'm retired, and if I were
still working, if I lost my job,

60
00:04:53,759 --> 00:04:56,319
that would be terrible.

61
00:04:56,395 --> 00:04:57,692
MAN:
Could I talk to your husband?

62
00:04:57,763 --> 00:05:01,426
WOMAN: No, but there's something
I would love to say to you.

63
00:05:01,500 --> 00:05:05,197
Aren't you guys happy working
at the Hormel plant?

64
00:05:05,270 --> 00:05:07,101
Under the current conditions,
no.

65
00:05:07,172 --> 00:05:11,233
We were happy making $10.69 and
when Hormel treated us decent.

66
00:05:11,310 --> 00:05:14,143
Why do you stay at
a place you're not happy?

67
00:05:14,213 --> 00:05:17,114
We don't have all the money
in the world like the Knowltons.

68
00:05:17,182 --> 00:05:20,481
There are so many people that
would love to have your job

69
00:05:20,552 --> 00:05:24,579
at $8.75 an hour
and all those nice benefits.

70
00:05:24,656 --> 00:05:27,784
When we were your age,
we weren't making what you were.

71
00:05:27,860 --> 00:05:30,795
Then give us a fair shake
like you got a fair shake.

72
00:05:30,863 --> 00:05:32,854
[ Door closes ]

73
00:05:35,567 --> 00:05:36,761
Hmm.

74
00:06:16,041 --> 00:06:20,808
If we gotta give up 23% wages
and 30% cut in benefits,

75
00:06:20,879 --> 00:06:23,279
when the company's
making $30 million,

76
00:06:23,348 --> 00:06:26,476
what are we gonna have to give
when they show a loss?

77
00:06:29,488 --> 00:06:31,718
Two years ago
under the incentive program,

78
00:06:31,790 --> 00:06:35,749
my last incentive check
in the hog cut in the new plant,

79
00:06:35,828 --> 00:06:41,266
I grossed $637
for 47 hours' work.

80
00:06:41,333 --> 00:06:45,201
After the incentive program
was taken away,

81
00:06:45,270 --> 00:06:48,205
I went down to $409 a week.

82
00:06:49,374 --> 00:06:53,208
Today I'm making $312.

83
00:06:53,278 --> 00:06:57,681
Working twice as hard
for the same amount of hours.

84
00:06:57,749 --> 00:06:59,478
It's ridiculous.

85
00:07:03,789 --> 00:07:07,122
My father worked
for George A. Hormel plant

86
00:07:07,192 --> 00:07:08,181
for many years.

87
00:07:08,260 --> 00:07:11,491
He was also a very proud man.
He was a hard worker.

88
00:07:11,563 --> 00:07:13,224
He was proud of his products.

89
00:07:13,298 --> 00:07:15,163
He was in the days
of heavy production.

90
00:07:15,234 --> 00:07:19,170
He went out on a stretcher
one day from the plant.

91
00:07:19,238 --> 00:07:23,937
My husband now, I'm proud
to be a wife of a hog cutter.

92
00:07:24,009 --> 00:07:25,806
I'm proud of the products.

93
00:07:25,878 --> 00:07:28,346
But I don't like the way
they're treating my family

94
00:07:28,413 --> 00:07:32,611
or my husband or anyone else
who ever worked for that plant.

95
00:07:32,684 --> 00:07:34,276
[ Cheers and applause ]

96
00:07:34,353 --> 00:07:37,083
JIM: It's a real quagmire
of a situation,

97
00:07:37,155 --> 00:07:40,124
and people
are really getting hurt.

98
00:07:44,196 --> 00:07:45,390
Their pride is hurt

99
00:07:45,464 --> 00:07:48,797
because they can't fulfill
the needs of their family,

100
00:07:48,867 --> 00:07:53,099
and they've somehow got to go
on welfare programs,

101
00:07:53,171 --> 00:07:57,130
and people are very angry,
hurt, upset, frustrated.

102
00:07:57,209 --> 00:08:00,144
And it's difficult
to vent your frustrations

103
00:08:00,212 --> 00:08:02,544
in the proper direction.

104
00:08:02,614 --> 00:08:04,047
WOMAN:
Utility workers make more.

105
00:08:04,116 --> 00:08:05,708
Meter readers make more.

106
00:08:05,784 --> 00:08:08,685
The garbage collectors
make more.

107
00:08:08,754 --> 00:08:12,485
A guy that works with Wes, or
did work with my husband quit.

108
00:08:12,558 --> 00:08:14,048
He got hired at the city.

109
00:08:14,126 --> 00:08:16,959
He's starting
at $11-something an hour.

110
00:08:17,029 --> 00:08:18,724
But I don't begrudge anybody

111
00:08:18,797 --> 00:08:21,960
that's making $30,000,
$40,000, $50,000.

112
00:08:22,034 --> 00:08:24,468
But let us live in our house.

113
00:08:24,536 --> 00:08:27,505
Let us live
in our $32,000 house.

114
00:08:37,482 --> 00:08:44,217
<i>And that we all
may walk in faith</i>

115
00:08:44,289 --> 00:08:48,487
<i>In your community</i>

116
00:08:48,560 --> 00:08:50,619
NYBERG:
In Austin, 22,000 people.

117
00:08:50,696 --> 00:08:53,392
We're in a little world
by ourselves down here.

118
00:08:53,465 --> 00:08:55,399
These are the people
we go to church with.

119
00:08:55,467 --> 00:08:57,697
These are the people
we go to grocery stores with.

120
00:08:57,769 --> 00:08:59,737
We meet on the street.

121
00:08:59,805 --> 00:09:02,569
We meet in various forms
of recreation.

122
00:09:02,641 --> 00:09:06,577
We rub shoulders with them.
Do we care about our employees?

123
00:09:06,645 --> 00:09:08,237
Yes, we do.

124
00:09:08,313 --> 00:09:09,940
But in the long term,

125
00:09:10,015 --> 00:09:12,848
we don't want to go the way
of many other packers

126
00:09:12,918 --> 00:09:17,116
who realized too late that
their costs were out of line

127
00:09:17,189 --> 00:09:20,124
and then tried to recover
and couldn't.

128
00:09:31,903 --> 00:09:33,370
<i>FILM NARRATOR:
It's been written that Jay</i>

129
00:09:33,438 --> 00:09:34,598
<i>was a born innovator</i>

130
00:09:34,673 --> 00:09:36,868
<i>and remembered
for his social conscience.</i>

131
00:09:36,942 --> 00:09:39,035
<i>His thoughtful understanding of</i>

132
00:09:39,111 --> 00:09:41,944
<i>and concern for the welfare
of the working man</i>

133
00:09:42,014 --> 00:09:44,539
<i>was surely what gave rise
to the benefits</i>

134
00:09:44,616 --> 00:09:47,983
<i>that have been made available
to Hormel personnel.</i>

135
00:09:48,053 --> 00:09:50,886
<i>He initiated the first
guaranteed annual wage.</i>

136
00:09:50,956 --> 00:09:52,753
<i>There was also
a first-of-its-kind</i>

137
00:09:52,824 --> 00:09:54,815
<i>profit-sharing plan
for the workers</i>

138
00:09:54,893 --> 00:09:57,726
<i>that paid a share of
the profits to each of them.</i>

139
00:09:57,796 --> 00:10:00,321
<i>Perhaps that explains
why everyone at Hormel</i>

140
00:10:00,399 --> 00:10:03,926
<i>strives for quality
and efficiency.</i>

141
00:10:04,002 --> 00:10:09,167
WOMAN: I've worked for Hormel,
it'll be 43 years this year.

142
00:10:10,742 --> 00:10:17,443
And if it were necessary
as a survival,

143
00:10:17,516 --> 00:10:20,451
I would be all for it.

144
00:10:20,519 --> 00:10:24,922
We've done it before
over the many, many times.

145
00:10:24,990 --> 00:10:29,393
But this, I think, is just
the mood of the industry,

146
00:10:29,461 --> 00:10:31,656
and they're jumping
on the bandwagon

147
00:10:31,730 --> 00:10:34,995
to be one of them to say,
"We were able to do it, too."

148
00:10:35,067 --> 00:10:38,969
Where, I think, if they
would have left our wages

149
00:10:39,037 --> 00:10:41,505
at their present standard,

150
00:10:41,573 --> 00:10:46,237
people would have really
used them as a shining example

151
00:10:46,311 --> 00:10:50,611
that in hard times, if you
really have good productivity,

152
00:10:50,682 --> 00:10:53,480
good relationship
with your employees,

153
00:10:53,552 --> 00:10:57,488
that you're able to handle
the bad times.

154
00:10:57,556 --> 00:11:00,320
I hope that they have
enough of the vision

155
00:11:00,392 --> 00:11:03,225
that I think I must have
for the welfare

156
00:11:03,295 --> 00:11:05,627
of the long-term future
of the company,

157
00:11:05,697 --> 00:11:09,189
that would say,
"We can do no more."

158
00:11:09,267 --> 00:11:12,794
If Jay Hormel were here today,
if George A. Hormel were here,

159
00:11:12,871 --> 00:11:15,806
they probably would be doing
exactly the same thing

160
00:11:15,874 --> 00:11:17,398
that we are.

161
00:11:25,384 --> 00:11:28,649
I think unions are getting
their teeth kicked in.

162
00:11:28,720 --> 00:11:31,951
I think if you're
into a situation

163
00:11:32,023 --> 00:11:34,082
of where you're getting beat up,

164
00:11:34,159 --> 00:11:36,559
you better try
something different.

165
00:11:36,628 --> 00:11:40,029
MAN: Corporate campaigns
initiated by Ray Rogers...

166
00:11:40,098 --> 00:11:41,588
MAN #2: Rogers
has been used to targeting

167
00:11:41,666 --> 00:11:42,894
one enemy, the employer.

168
00:11:42,968 --> 00:11:45,300
MAN #3: Rogers brought
his Corporate Campaign here...

169
00:11:45,370 --> 00:11:49,101
JIM: We were very ineffective
in communicating our message.

170
00:11:49,174 --> 00:11:50,903
MAN #4:
He managed to attract reporters

171
00:11:50,976 --> 00:11:52,967
from the "New York Times,"
the "Chicago Tribune"...

172
00:11:53,044 --> 00:11:56,946
JIM: I ran across an article on
Ray Rogers and gave him a call.

173
00:11:57,015 --> 00:11:58,812
MAN #5: Tough-talking
labor consultant...

174
00:11:58,884 --> 00:12:01,717
JIM: He said he needed
to do a little research

175
00:12:01,787 --> 00:12:04,255
because he was a vegetarian,

176
00:12:04,322 --> 00:12:06,882
didn't know anything
about meatpacking.

177
00:12:10,395 --> 00:12:13,796
Ray came and made a
presentation to our membership.

178
00:12:16,902 --> 00:12:20,099
RAY: We will run
a multimillion dollar campaign

179
00:12:20,172 --> 00:12:24,438
even though you don't
have millions of dollars.

180
00:12:24,509 --> 00:12:27,501
The greatest resource,
the greatest strength you have

181
00:12:27,579 --> 00:12:30,047
is the people themselves.

182
00:12:30,115 --> 00:12:32,083
And that's why
we feel so confident

183
00:12:32,150 --> 00:12:34,550
that we can pull off
a major victory,

184
00:12:34,619 --> 00:12:36,814
not just for Local P-9
in Austin,

185
00:12:36,888 --> 00:12:39,584
but for labor
throughout this entire country.

186
00:13:06,685 --> 00:13:08,516
- Congratulations, partner.
- Yeah.

187
00:13:08,587 --> 00:13:10,953
The price of poker just went up.

188
00:13:11,022 --> 00:13:14,583
In this game, because that's
the way the company views it.

189
00:13:14,659 --> 00:13:17,992
It's a game the way
they want to treat people,

190
00:13:18,063 --> 00:13:20,554
hold their whole lives
in jeopardy.

191
00:13:20,632 --> 00:13:23,157
And to them, it might be a game.

192
00:13:23,235 --> 00:13:26,636
And to us, it's a war.

193
00:13:26,705 --> 00:13:28,673
Things can really
start moving now.

194
00:13:28,740 --> 00:13:31,732
Super.
That's just really nice.

195
00:13:32,777 --> 00:13:36,269
And we hope that the corporate
executives from Hormel come.

196
00:13:36,348 --> 00:13:38,714
We hope the executives
from the bank come.

197
00:13:38,783 --> 00:13:41,274
We want everybody to see
the type of program

198
00:13:41,353 --> 00:13:42,581
that we plan on running

199
00:13:42,654 --> 00:13:46,090
and then let them begin
to lose the night's sleep

200
00:13:46,157 --> 00:13:49,991
like they've caused
this community to lose sleep.

201
00:13:51,596 --> 00:13:52,858
[ Chanting ]
We're gonna win!

202
00:13:52,931 --> 00:13:55,331
We're gonna win!
We're gonna win!

203
00:13:55,400 --> 00:13:58,426
We're gonna win!
We're gonna win!

204
00:14:05,544 --> 00:14:08,172
RAY: On our staff,
we have experts in all facets

205
00:14:08,246 --> 00:14:11,773
of research and analysis,
communications experts,

206
00:14:11,850 --> 00:14:13,875
and experts in all facets

207
00:14:13,952 --> 00:14:15,715
of political
and community organization.

208
00:14:15,787 --> 00:14:19,314
We looked out there in society
and saw poor and working people

209
00:14:19,391 --> 00:14:20,722
getting the daylights
kicked out of them.

210
00:14:20,792 --> 00:14:24,319
We felt there had to be
a mechanism that they and unions

211
00:14:24,396 --> 00:14:25,988
and community groups
could turn to

212
00:14:26,064 --> 00:14:28,965
that had a lot of expertise
in how to challenge

213
00:14:29,034 --> 00:14:31,093
powerful adversaries
that were irresponsible

214
00:14:31,169 --> 00:14:32,796
in the policies
directed at workers.

215
00:14:32,871 --> 00:14:35,203
So we developed
Corporate Campaign programs.

216
00:14:35,273 --> 00:14:38,071
And our campaign is one
of taking the offense,

217
00:14:38,143 --> 00:14:40,077
showing that workers
can fight back.

218
00:14:40,145 --> 00:14:43,581
That they don't have to keep
taking one loss after another.

219
00:14:45,283 --> 00:14:46,978
You know what we need to do.

220
00:14:47,052 --> 00:14:51,079
JIM: Ray told me you're never
going to outspend a company,

221
00:14:51,156 --> 00:14:53,215
public-relations-wise.

222
00:14:53,291 --> 00:14:56,021
My name is Ray Rogers.
I'm with Corporate Campaign.

223
00:14:56,094 --> 00:14:57,789
JIM:
That what you needed to do

224
00:14:57,862 --> 00:14:59,693
was look at creating a situation

225
00:14:59,764 --> 00:15:02,358
that became
a newsworthy situation.

226
00:15:02,434 --> 00:15:06,427
The company spent millions in
many years to build an image.

227
00:15:06,504 --> 00:15:07,937
That's being destroyed
overnight.

228
00:15:08,006 --> 00:15:11,134
JIM: The strategy was
to go after the money

229
00:15:11,209 --> 00:15:12,471
behind the corporation.

230
00:15:12,544 --> 00:15:15,206
There's a lot of labor money
in First Bank's system.

231
00:15:15,280 --> 00:15:16,941
MAN: Ray Rogers
and his Corporate Campaign

232
00:15:17,015 --> 00:15:20,644
mailed this letter to over 5,000
union members in the Midwest

233
00:15:20,719 --> 00:15:22,983
that says in part
the First Bank system

234
00:15:23,054 --> 00:15:25,750
is a principal stockholder
in the Hormel company

235
00:15:25,824 --> 00:15:27,951
and thus can influence policy.

236
00:15:28,026 --> 00:15:30,654
This institution
is directly involved

237
00:15:30,729 --> 00:15:32,856
in the policymaking process
of Hormel.

238
00:15:32,931 --> 00:15:37,595
JIM: Ray knows how to put
labor's best foot forward

239
00:15:37,669 --> 00:15:41,196
so that John Q. Public would
sympathize with our cause.

240
00:15:41,272 --> 00:15:44,002
There's some guy I'd never seen.

