gonna give you anything else.

1214
01:08:13,455 --> 01:08:17,186
Now we're looking at shutting
the other operations down.

1215
01:08:17,259 --> 01:08:18,283
Don't you feel

1216
01:08:18,360 --> 01:08:23,525
that that's a much more
pressurizing strategy

1217
01:08:23,599 --> 01:08:25,863
on this company at this time?

1218
01:08:25,934 --> 01:08:29,426
Especially in light of the fact
that those people know

1219
01:08:29,505 --> 01:08:32,599
that whatever happens here
is gonna happen to them.

1220
01:08:32,675 --> 01:08:34,472
We need to communicate that.

1221
01:08:34,543 --> 01:08:35,703
Mm-hmm.

1222
01:08:35,778 --> 01:08:39,179
Don't you think that that's
a better position to be into?

1223
01:08:39,248 --> 01:08:41,739
If you can't shut them down
completely,

1224
01:08:41,817 --> 01:08:42,943
you've accomplished nothing,

1225
01:08:43,018 --> 01:08:47,614
other than getting a whole lot
of people fired and out of work.

1226
01:08:47,690 --> 01:08:52,855
What I'm saying to you is,
at what cost are you prepared

1227
01:08:52,928 --> 01:08:55,829
to take roving pickets
to that plant?

1228
01:08:55,898 --> 01:08:57,559
What are you gonna
do when they say,

1229
01:08:57,633 --> 01:09:01,592
"You screwed me out of a job.
Now what are you gonna do?"

1230
01:09:01,670 --> 01:09:05,162
I'll say it. Hell, there's
nothing we can do for them.

1231
01:09:05,240 --> 01:09:06,605
That's the risk we take.

1232
01:09:06,675 --> 01:09:08,040
Not we take.
They take.

1233
01:09:08,110 --> 01:09:09,771
Okay.
It's the risk they take.

1234
01:09:09,845 --> 01:09:11,779
We all take.

1235
01:09:11,847 --> 01:09:15,681
Yeah, we took it willingly,
and we took it to start with.

1236
01:09:15,751 --> 01:09:18,584
Now for our fight,
we're dragging them in.

1237
01:09:18,654 --> 01:09:21,350
JIM: When does the realization
come to those folks

1238
01:09:21,423 --> 01:09:24,187
that our fight
is indeed their fight?

1239
01:09:24,259 --> 01:09:27,660
When are we gonna do it
if we don't do it now?

1240
01:09:27,730 --> 01:09:29,891
Mr. Nyberg, what will Hormel do

1241
01:09:29,965 --> 01:09:33,594
if P-9 sets up picket lines
at your other plants?

1242
01:09:33,669 --> 01:09:36,229
Our employees know
that it is our position

1243
01:09:36,305 --> 01:09:39,274
that they'd be in violation
of the contracts

1244
01:09:39,341 --> 01:09:41,775
if they voluntarily stay out

1245
01:09:41,844 --> 01:09:43,709
and honor the picket line
of Local P-9

1246
01:09:43,779 --> 01:09:46,077
or however many pickets
there might be.

1247
01:09:46,148 --> 01:09:48,616
We know that if they do stay out

1248
01:09:48,684 --> 01:09:51,710
that they will be subject
to replacement

1249
01:09:51,787 --> 01:09:55,120
just as employees in Austin
are subject to replacement.

1250
01:09:57,659 --> 01:09:59,923
<i>The Executive Board
of Local P-9</i>

1251
01:09:59,995 --> 01:10:02,862
<i>decided to recommend that
the picket line be extended</i>

1252
01:10:02,931 --> 01:10:07,834
<i>to all other Hormel plants in
an attempt to shut them down.</i>

1253
01:10:07,903 --> 01:10:10,701
<i>With that came the promise that
if anyone at the other plants</i>

1254
01:10:10,773 --> 01:10:13,970
<i>got fired for honoring
P-9's picket line,</i>

1255
01:10:14,042 --> 01:10:16,408
<i>no P-9ers
would return to their jobs</i>

1256
01:10:16,478 --> 01:10:20,175
<i>until the company agreed
to rehire everyone.</i>

1257
01:10:21,583 --> 01:10:25,679
You know, when you talk
about being illegal,

1258
01:10:25,754 --> 01:10:30,748
at one time, it was illegal
to go out on strike.

1259
01:10:30,826 --> 01:10:34,694
At one time, it was illegal
to join a union.

1260
01:10:34,763 --> 01:10:36,094
I guess at one time,

1261
01:10:36,165 --> 01:10:39,965
it was illegal
for America to even exist.

1262
01:10:40,936 --> 01:10:44,337
The Executive Board
has passed a motion.

1263
01:10:44,406 --> 01:10:47,375
Roving pickets will be sent
to other plants.

1264
01:10:49,211 --> 01:10:54,080
If this is approved, it'll send
a message to the company,

1265
01:10:54,149 --> 01:10:56,709
to everyone else.

1266
01:10:56,785 --> 01:10:58,946
We made a promise.

1267
01:10:59,021 --> 01:11:04,857
We swore we'd always remember.
No retreat, no surrender.

1268
01:11:06,595 --> 01:11:08,563
Speaking on the motion...

1269
01:11:10,165 --> 01:11:13,692
It's a unanimous
Executive Board recommendation.

1270
01:11:15,137 --> 01:11:18,106
All those in favor
signify by saying "aye."

1271
01:11:18,173 --> 01:11:20,573
CROWD:
Aye!

1272
01:11:20,642 --> 01:11:22,735
Those opposed.

1273
01:11:22,811 --> 01:11:24,278
Ayes have it.

1274
01:11:38,560 --> 01:11:41,552
I repeat.
This is a union picket line.

1275
01:11:41,630 --> 01:11:44,690
We ask that you do not cross it.

1276
01:11:44,766 --> 01:11:47,963
Take the day off.
One damn day is all we ask.

1277
01:11:48,036 --> 01:11:52,200
All Hormel plants will be shut
up tight as a drum by Friday.

1278
01:11:52,274 --> 01:11:54,902
There will be none running,
to our knowledge.

1279
01:11:54,977 --> 01:11:56,638
We'd appreciate your support.

1280
01:11:56,712 --> 01:11:58,270
Go home and have
a cup of coffee.

1281
01:11:58,347 --> 01:12:01,976
Go talk to Ma and the kids
before they go to school.

1282
01:12:02,050 --> 01:12:04,280
MAN:
There's no way on God's creation

1283
01:12:04,353 --> 01:12:06,821
that I'm gonna cross
their picket line!

1284
01:12:10,025 --> 01:12:12,255
When I looked at a guy
I worked with for seven years.

1285
01:12:12,327 --> 01:12:15,819
I live in the same town he does,
22 miles up the road.

1286
01:12:15,898 --> 01:12:17,991
And I said to him,
"How do you feel?"

1287
01:12:18,066 --> 01:12:19,556
He said, "My heart's pumping."

1288
01:12:19,635 --> 01:12:21,762
I looked at another guy
I worked with for seven years.

1289
01:12:21,837 --> 01:12:25,170
I said, "How do you feel?"
He said, "My heart's pumping."

1290
01:12:25,240 --> 01:12:27,708
I said, "Guess what?
You're union people."

1291
01:12:27,776 --> 01:12:30,506
We ain't crossing
no picket lines!

1292
01:12:30,579 --> 01:12:32,774
We ain't crossing them!

1293
01:12:46,862 --> 01:12:50,195
What miracle do we expect to
happen in the next three days?

1294
01:12:50,265 --> 01:12:52,096
That's the question.

1295
01:12:52,901 --> 01:12:56,268
What miracle?
How or why?

1296
01:12:56,338 --> 01:12:59,603
We have tremendous spirit,
we've got a wonderful program.

1297
01:12:59,674 --> 01:13:03,542
And we seem to think that
if we just go one day at a time,

1298
01:13:03,612 --> 01:13:04,670
like an alcoholic.

1299
01:13:04,746 --> 01:13:07,408
Just keep the strike going
one more day,

1300
01:13:07,482 --> 01:13:12,044
and after today's over,
it'll keep going tomorrow.

1301
01:13:12,120 --> 01:13:15,419
What do we expect
is gonna happen?

1302
01:13:15,490 --> 01:13:17,253
I'm mystified.

1303
01:13:25,267 --> 01:13:26,427
Scabs!

1304
01:13:26,501 --> 01:13:28,992
Go back to your own town, scabs!

1305
01:13:29,070 --> 01:13:32,938
Asshole! Go to hell!
I hope you rot in hell!

1306
01:13:36,811 --> 01:13:39,211
You're the one
that really hurts, Steve.

1307
01:13:39,281 --> 01:13:41,374
All these other guys are dicks.

1308
01:13:41,449 --> 01:13:44,782
When you went across there,
you really hurt.

1309
01:13:44,853 --> 01:13:46,514
What the hell's
the matter with you?

1310
01:13:46,588 --> 01:13:48,488
How can you work
with those scabs?

1311
01:13:48,556 --> 01:13:52,083
Doesn't it bother you to go in
there with guys like that?

1312
01:13:52,160 --> 01:13:53,525
Then you got no class.

1313
01:13:53,595 --> 01:13:55,358
I don't know you.

1314
01:13:55,430 --> 01:13:56,897
Who's your smiley partner?

1315
01:13:56,965 --> 01:13:59,866
I've known that guy
since we were in grade school.

1316
01:14:03,772 --> 01:14:06,468
It's killing him inside.
He's told me that.

1317
01:14:06,541 --> 01:14:09,840
I tried to talk him out of it.

1318
01:14:09,911 --> 01:14:12,744
He said no.
It's what he had to do.

1319
01:14:14,115 --> 01:14:16,845
My wife and children
have been my backbone.

1320
01:14:16,918 --> 01:14:18,385
They've just.
"No way."

1321
01:14:18,453 --> 01:14:22,412
They knew in their minds
that if I did,

1322
01:14:22,490 --> 01:14:24,720
I couldn't live with myself.

1323
01:14:28,096 --> 01:14:30,621
RON: If things haven't changed
substantially

1324
01:14:30,699 --> 01:14:32,792
in two or three days,

1325
01:14:32,867 --> 01:14:36,735
I will base my decision
on the fact

1326
01:14:36,805 --> 01:14:39,865
that my family is number one
in my life, not my union.

1327
01:14:39,941 --> 01:14:42,808
NARRATOR: Are you gonna go
across the picket line?

1328
01:14:42,877 --> 01:14:44,811
So it appears it.

1329
01:14:44,879 --> 01:14:48,940
At this stage of the game,
well, it would be tough,

1330
01:14:49,017 --> 01:14:53,954
but I can't see any alternative.

1331
01:14:54,022 --> 01:14:57,185
Now that we've been working on
this for a year and a half

1332
01:14:57,258 --> 01:14:58,816
trying to figure out
the difference

1333
01:14:58,893 --> 01:15:00,360
between right and wrong,

1334
01:15:00,428 --> 01:15:03,556
I believe that I was a dupe,
I was lied to originally.

1335
01:15:03,631 --> 01:15:06,725
And now he's got control
of my whole life.

1336
01:15:06,801 --> 01:15:09,463
On the other hand,
it's a question of morality,

1337
01:15:09,537 --> 01:15:11,129
because I was brought up

1338
01:15:11,206 --> 01:15:13,834
that you do not cross a
picket line, no matter what.

1339
01:15:13,908 --> 01:15:15,808
It's something
that you do not do.

1340
01:15:15,877 --> 01:15:18,641
Because you don't belong
to a union all these years

1341
01:15:18,713 --> 01:15:20,738
and develop
all these principles.

1342
01:15:20,815 --> 01:15:22,942
It isn't like a dollar bill.

1343
01:15:23,018 --> 01:15:25,452
You can't throw it on the ground
and be rid of it.

1344
01:15:25,520 --> 01:15:28,717
As much as I want my job back,

1345
01:15:28,790 --> 01:15:32,590
I've still been a good
union member for many years.

1346
01:15:32,660 --> 01:15:35,390
But I don't know.

1347
01:15:35,463 --> 01:15:36,862
My family comes first.

1348
01:15:36,931 --> 01:15:39,957
My daughter goes to work.
She's got a part-time job.

1349
01:15:40,035 --> 01:15:43,004
My boy, he works at McDonald's,
part-time job.

1350
01:15:43,071 --> 01:15:45,733
My wife goes to work.
She's got a job.

1351
01:15:45,807 --> 01:15:49,106
And what do I do? I sit home,
and I play with the cat.

1352
01:15:49,177 --> 01:15:51,372
What kind of provider is that?

1353
01:15:51,446 --> 01:15:52,504
It may sound corny,

1354
01:15:52,580 --> 01:15:55,208
but a person takes pride
in being a breadwinner

1355
01:15:55,283 --> 01:15:58,047
and providing for your family.

1356
01:15:58,119 --> 01:15:59,416
When you can't do that,

1357
01:15:59,487 --> 01:16:02,251
when you say to them,
"All I want to do is work,"

1358
01:16:02,323 --> 01:16:04,518
and they...

1359
01:16:04,592 --> 01:16:05,820
It's tough.

1360
01:16:05,894 --> 01:16:11,696
But I spent more
than we should have.

1361
01:16:11,766 --> 01:16:15,133
But I want to go back to work.

1362
01:16:15,203 --> 01:16:18,536
And the hell with P-9.

1363
01:16:18,606 --> 01:16:21,097
I'm ready.

1364
01:16:21,176 --> 01:16:22,438
NARRATOR:
Is that hard for you?

1365
01:16:22,510 --> 01:16:23,442
You bet.

1366
01:16:23,511 --> 01:16:25,479
Why?

1367
01:16:25,547 --> 01:16:27,708
Not being able to -- excuse me.

1368
01:16:27,782 --> 01:16:30,216
[ Voice breaking ]
Provide for my family.

1369
01:16:30,285 --> 01:16:31,877
[ Crying ]

1370
01:16:38,293 --> 01:16:40,488
I just can't talk no more.

1371
01:18:00,041 --> 01:18:03,477
You're scared to see all them
people you've worked with.

1372
01:18:07,882 --> 01:18:10,783
All these people are standing
there hollering at you.

1373
01:18:10,852 --> 01:18:13,446
Yet, you know
you have to go across.

1374
01:18:15,857 --> 01:18:17,791
there's some in there,
you think,

1375
01:18:17,859 --> 01:18:20,453
"I don't care
if you ever come back."

1376
01:18:22,230 --> 01:18:24,323
You see people
you talk to every day,

1377
01:18:24,399 --> 01:18:26,264
and it almost makes you cry.

1378
01:18:26,334 --> 01:18:28,564
There are some good friends
of mine.

1379
01:18:35,476 --> 01:18:38,172
That's the ones
you feel like you're betraying.

1380
01:18:47,055 --> 01:18:48,647
- Where you guys going?
- To work.

1381
01:18:48,723 --> 01:18:51,590
- You got a pass for that?
- You want to see our cards?

1382
01:18:51,659 --> 01:18:54,059
Just Hormel cards?
You want to see them?

1383
01:18:54,128 --> 01:18:56,323
Yeah.
You new employees?

1384
01:18:56,397 --> 01:18:59,798
No, no. Not by any stretch
of the imagination.

1385
01:19:00,735 --> 01:19:04,364
WOMAN: To some, staying out
no longer makes sense.

1386
01:19:04,439 --> 01:19:06,634
There is more here
than a town divided,

1387
01:19:06,708 --> 01:19:09,176
as brother watches brother
cross the line

1388
01:19:09,244 --> 01:19:14,944
in a place not big enough for
anyone to hide for very long.

1389
01:19:15,016 --> 01:19:18,144
He won't be my brother
if he crosses the line.

1390
01:19:24,425 --> 01:19:29,624
For me, it wasn't tough
to get to the point of the gate.

1391
01:19:29,697 --> 01:19:30,527
I was ready.

1392
01:19:30,598 --> 01:19:34,056
But the minute
we crossed that line,

1393
01:19:34,135 --> 01:19:36,467
part of me
just stayed back there.

1394
01:19:36,537 --> 01:19:39,870
Well, unionism, to me,
is watching out

1395
01:19:39,941 --> 01:19:43,104
not only for your own job,
but you're an organization

1396
01:19:43,177 --> 01:19:45,805
for the welfare and benefit
of all the workers.

1397
01:19:45,880 --> 01:19:51,147
And now, you know,
for this moment, we aren't.

1398
01:19:51,219 --> 01:19:52,846
Because we left them.

1399
01:19:56,024 --> 01:19:59,152
You know, I wasn't always
International president.

1400
01:19:59,227 --> 01:20:02,060
I used to work
in the grocery stores, you know.

1401
01:20:02,130 --> 01:20:04,621
And I know what it is
to work for peanuts.

1402
01:20:04,699 --> 01:20:06,599
And you think I like the fact

1403
01:20:06,668 --> 01:20:09,728
that our people got to roll
their wages back a bit?

1404
01:20:09,804 --> 01:20:10,600
I don't.

1405
01:20:10,672 --> 01:20:12,367
But I tell you what.

1406
01:20:12,440 --> 01:20:14,408
I don't take people
over a cliff.

1407
01:20:14,475 --> 01:20:17,000
There's an old rule
in the labor movement.

1408
01:20:17,078 --> 01:20:19,706
Anybody can put people
on the street.

1409
01:20:19,781 --> 01:20:22,341
It takes a man to put them
back to work. I'm sorry.

1410
01:20:22,417 --> 01:20:25,147
It takes a man or a woman
to put them back to work.

1411
01:20:25,219 --> 01:20:27,687
Now is the time to settle it.

1412
01:20:27,755 --> 01:20:29,222
Hopefully, we can work it out

1413
01:20:29,290 --> 01:20:32,020
through the course
of our local union.

1414
01:20:32,093 --> 01:20:36,086
If we don't, then in a short
period of time, I'll settle it.

1415
01:20:36,164 --> 01:20:37,893
- Question.
- I'll settle it.

1416
01:20:37,965 --> 01:20:41,731
- How will you settle it?
- I told you I'll settle it.

1417
01:20:41,803 --> 01:20:43,668
I have a meeting.
Thank you.

1418
01:20:45,506 --> 01:20:47,997
The United Food and Commercial
Workers Union

1419
01:20:48,076 --> 01:20:50,772
ordered 1,000 members
of its meatpackers local

1420
01:20:50,845 --> 01:20:52,972
to end their bitter
seven-month strike

1421
01:20:53,047 --> 01:20:55,277
against Hormel
in Austin, Minnesota.

1422
01:20:55,349 --> 01:20:57,544
The International Union said
it had lifted its sanction

1423
01:20:57,618 --> 01:20:58,312
of the walkout

1424
01:20:58,386 --> 01:21:01,253
and cut off $40-a-week benefits
to strikers.

1425
01:21:01,322 --> 01:21:03,654
But pickets remained in place
through the day.

1426
01:21:03,725 --> 01:21:05,693
WOMAN: It is a strike,
those on the line say,

1427
01:21:05,760 --> 01:21:07,819
is becoming symbolic
of the struggle

1428
01:21:07,895 --> 01:21:10,056
to keep trade unions alive.

1429
01:21:14,902 --> 01:21:19,032
If they end up operating
that plant nonunion

1430
01:21:19,107 --> 01:21:22,736
and your guys
never get back in there,

1431
01:21:22,810 --> 01:21:25,779
will you consider that
a big defeat for you?

1432
01:21:25,847 --> 01:21:27,371
Or not?

1433
01:21:27,448 --> 01:21:29,507
Number one,

1434
01:21:29,584 --> 01:21:32,815
if I say there's no way I could
look at this as a defeat,

1435
01:21:32,887 --> 01:21:35,720
then you're gonna say,
"How can you say that?

1436
01:21:35,790 --> 01:21:38,691
Now, you either win
or you're gonna lose."

1437
01:21:38,760 --> 01:21:42,628
And let's talk about
what has happened here

1438
01:21:42,697 --> 01:21:46,360
and about the types of
victory and defeat you can have.

1439
01:21:46,434 --> 01:21:49,198
If all the workers
lose their job here,

1440
01:21:49,270 --> 01:21:52,137
okay, if that's a scenario
that you're playing,

1441
01:21:52,206 --> 01:21:55,733
yeah, that is certainly
a defeat that way.

1442
01:21:55,810 --> 01:21:59,337
But when you consider the fight
these people have fought.

1443
01:21:59,413 --> 01:22:02,075
Are you saying that 1,000 guys
lose their jobs,

1444
01:22:02,150 --> 01:22:04,846
and because they've got
intense national attention

1445
01:22:04,919 --> 01:22:07,615
on these important problems
that confront labor,

1446
01:22:07,688 --> 01:22:09,053
that could still be a victory?

1447
01:22:09,123 --> 01:22:10,556
No, what I am saying,

1448
01:22:10,625 --> 01:22:13,321
there's been a set of dynamics
that has occurred

1449
01:22:13,394 --> 01:22:16,886
both with all the people in this
area, within this community,

1450
01:22:16,964 --> 01:22:19,432
and within the labor movement.

1451
01:22:19,500 --> 01:22:23,334
That cannot be considered
anything but positive.

1452
01:22:41,189 --> 01:22:44,784
JIM:
I think that we at P-9

1453
01:22:44,859 --> 01:22:48,192
started
this small labor dispute.

1454
01:22:48,262 --> 01:22:51,459
It quickly escalated
into a labor dispute

1455
01:22:51,532 --> 01:22:54,126
that represented
a lot of things.

1456
01:22:55,603 --> 01:23:00,040
Taking on one of the corporate
giants in an industry.

1457
01:23:00,107 --> 01:23:02,871
Taking on one of the largest
international unions

1458
01:23:02,944 --> 01:23:05,606
in the country.

1459
01:23:05,680 --> 01:23:08,547
And really recognizing
the forces

1460
01:23:08,616 --> 01:23:11,449
that working people
have to deal with.

1461
01:23:17,124 --> 01:23:22,892
If a small union in the middle
of a cornfield in Minnesota

1462
01:23:22,964 --> 01:23:27,424
can do the kinds of things
we do...

1463
01:23:28,236 --> 01:23:31,171
We just need to get about
the business of doing it.

1464
01:23:56,530 --> 01:23:59,465
LEWIE: I don't believe
the membership elects leaders

1465
01:23:59,533 --> 01:24:02,024
to be heroes at their expense.

1466
01:24:02,870 --> 01:24:05,498
Talks about dignity and
everybody going back together.

1467
01:24:05,573 --> 01:24:08,303
What dignity is there
when you don't have a job?

1468
01:24:08,376 --> 01:24:10,367
There's no dignity at all.

1469
01:24:16,851 --> 01:24:18,682
<i>In June of 1986,</i>

1470
01:24:18,753 --> 01:24:22,280
<i>the International took over
the local union</i>

1471
01:24:22,356 --> 01:24:26,486
<i>and threw out the elected
leadership of Local P-9.</i>

1472
01:24:26,560 --> 01:24:29,393
The main things
that the order covers is

1473
01:24:29,463 --> 01:24:36,335
if anybody physically confronts
the UFCW, if they remove assets,

1474
01:24:36,404 --> 01:24:41,000
or if they hold themselves out
to be representing Local P-9

1475
01:24:41,075 --> 01:24:43,066
rather than just saying
they're a member of P-9.

1476
01:24:43,144 --> 01:24:45,669
Do I have to say I'm suspended?

1477
01:24:45,746 --> 01:24:47,577
The order's
pretty clear on that.

1478
01:24:47,648 --> 01:24:49,707
I got to say I'm suspended?

1479
01:24:58,559 --> 01:24:59,924
<i>The International Union</i>

1480
01:24:59,994 --> 01:25:02,155
<i>negotiated a settlement
with Hormel,</i>

1481
01:25:02,229 --> 01:25:05,255
<i>whereby the people
who crossed the picket line</i>

1482
01:25:05,333 --> 01:25:08,268
<i>would receive the same wages
and benefits as workers</i>

1483
01:25:08,336 --> 01:25:10,964
<i>at the other Hormel plants.</i>

1484
01:25:11,038 --> 01:25:14,599
<i>$10.25 per hour.</i>

1485
01:25:19,013 --> 01:25:20,776
We didn't stand by the company.

1486
01:25:20,848 --> 01:25:23,681
We stood by
the International Union.

1487
01:25:23,751 --> 01:25:25,616
Kiss my ass!
Kiss my ass!

1488
01:25:25,686 --> 01:25:27,313
You're full of shit.

1489
01:25:27,388 --> 01:25:30,380
You went back to save
your ass and save your job.

1490
01:25:30,458 --> 01:25:32,016
By God, we needed our jobs.

1491
01:25:32,093 --> 01:25:34,891
We took our chances
with Hormel with the hope

1492
01:25:34,962 --> 01:25:37,988
that unionism
would somehow survive.

1493
01:25:38,065 --> 01:25:42,365
We left the union
and we went back to our jobs.

1494
01:25:42,937 --> 01:25:44,768
That's where it was.

1495
01:25:44,839 --> 01:25:46,500
[ Booing and jeering ]

1496
01:25:48,542 --> 01:25:50,567
Go ahead.
You can scream and holler.

1497
01:25:50,644 --> 01:25:53,078
Get that out of your system.
Then we can proceed.

1498
01:25:54,682 --> 01:25:58,345
There's one part in the contract
that I must have missed.

1499
01:25:58,419 --> 01:26:03,516
It's the part that says
they have to take me

1500
01:26:03,591 --> 01:26:06,287
and the rest
of all these guys back.

1501
01:26:06,360 --> 01:26:08,123
This is the way I feel.

1502
01:26:08,195 --> 01:26:12,063
Hormel's will never take me back
unless I put it in the contract

1503
01:26:12,133 --> 01:26:13,862
or you put it in the contract.

1504
01:26:13,934 --> 01:26:15,902
And if that's not
in the contract,

1505
01:26:15,970 --> 01:26:19,235
all this bullshit of a contract
don't mean nothing to me.

1506
01:26:19,306 --> 01:26:23,140
Because how many days' vacation
or how much of this they get.

1507
01:26:23,210 --> 01:26:27,544
I don't get none of it, because
I didn't get back in the plant.

1508
01:26:27,615 --> 01:26:30,584
<i>The contract did not contain
any provisions</i>

1509
01:26:30,651 --> 01:26:34,815
<i>for the people
who honored the picket line.</i>

1510
01:26:36,390 --> 01:26:40,292
<i>These people were placed
on a waiting list.</i>

1511
01:26:40,361 --> 01:26:43,762
It's time, and I think you
people have realized, too.

1512
01:26:43,831 --> 01:26:46,061
Had we pulled together
two years ago,

1513
01:26:46,133 --> 01:26:48,761
I don't think you or us
would be faced with this.

1514
01:26:48,836 --> 01:26:51,930
But I think it's the thing
that's going on in America,

1515
01:26:52,006 --> 01:26:54,873
and I think we as men and women
have to realize

1516
01:26:54,942 --> 01:26:56,239
we better start pulling
together,

1517
01:26:56,310 --> 01:26:59,006
or, by God,
they're gonna bury us.

1518
01:27:34,082 --> 01:27:36,846
Part of why
it's gonna be so hard to leave

1519
01:27:36,918 --> 01:27:39,546
is because I'm gonna have to
leave my mom and dad.

1520
01:27:39,621 --> 01:27:41,088
My dad's still out on strike,

1521
01:27:41,156 --> 01:27:44,751
and I feel like
I'm abandoning him, almost.

1522
01:27:44,826 --> 01:27:50,492
But we feel like we have to get
on with our lives for the kids.

1523
01:27:50,565 --> 01:27:52,897
They need a normal atmosphere
they can grow up in.

1524
01:27:52,967 --> 01:27:55,868
I know my dad will be okay,
'cause he's a survivor.

1525
01:27:55,937 --> 01:27:58,531
And he knows that
we're still behind him 100%.

1526
01:27:58,606 --> 01:27:59,903
We're not abandoning him.

1527
01:27:59,974 --> 01:28:03,432
We're just taking our fight
somewhere else.

1528
01:28:06,481 --> 01:28:09,814
As far as the strike goes,
it was time.

1529
01:28:09,884 --> 01:28:11,078
It was past time.

1530
01:28:11,152 --> 01:28:14,781
Mike took a stand and refused
to go across the picket line.

1531
01:28:14,856 --> 01:28:17,916
I'm glad he wouldn't, because
I wouldn't have wanted him to.

